// =============================================================================
// schema.zia — Columns, Rows, and the MVCC visibility check
// Part of ViperSQL  (package: engine)
// =============================================================================
//
// PURPOSE
// -------
// This file defines the two universal "shape of tabular data" types used
// by the whole engine:
//
//   * `Column` — a single column's *metadata*: name, type code, and the
//                whole pile of SQL-standard per-column decorations
//                (PRIMARY KEY, NOT NULL, UNIQUE, DEFAULT, FOREIGN KEY,
//                CHECK, GENERATED ALWAYS AS, named constraints).
//
//   * `Row`    — a single row of user data: a `List[SqlValue]` plus
//                MVCC bookkeeping (`xmin`, `xmax`, soft-deleted flag) so
//                concurrent transactions can see consistent snapshots.
//
// Everything downstream — the storage engine that serialises rows, the
// query planner that projects columns, the joins that glue rows together,
// the PG wire protocol that ships them to clients — is built around these
// two shapes.  Get the invariants here right and the rest of the engine
// has a single consistent vocabulary; get them wrong and you are patching
// every call site forever.
//
// WHERE THIS FITS
// ---------------
//     parser/*    →   builds SQL ASTs; those ASTs reference *columns* by
//                     name (String) — no schema knowledge yet.
//
//     engine/ddl  →   creates/alters `Table` objects whose `.columns` list
//                     is a `List[Column]` defined here.
//
//     engine/dml, query, executor
//                 →   produce and consume `Row` values with the `SqlValue`
//                     cell type from `types.zia`.
//
//     engine/result.zia
//                 →   embeds `List[Row]` as its row buffer.  See that file
//                     (already annotated earlier in this tutorial) for
//                     how results get rendered.
//
//     storage/*   →   serialises rows to pages (`data_page.zia`) and back
//                     through `storage/serializer.zia`.
//
// KEY DESIGN CHOICES
// ------------------
//   1. Columns own their defaults.  `hasDefault` + `defaultValue` live on
//      the column (not in a side table) so that INSERT/UPDATE can fill
//      missing cells with *one* lookup rather than joining against a
//      separate defaults map.  The cost is a bit of wasted space on
//      columns without defaults — trivial compared to the simplicity win.
//
//   2. Foreign-key action codes are integers, not a separate enum.  This
//      is a deliberate compromise: the lexer/parser already speaks the SQL
//      keywords (CASCADE / SET NULL / …), and at the Row-engine layer we
//      only ever *compare* actions, never display them, so an integer
//      comparison is all we need.  The named constants below document the
//      valid values.
//
//   3. MVCC visibility is a method on `Row` itself.  Alternatives — a
//      helper function in `txn.zia`, a `Visibility` struct — were rejected
//      because the visibility test runs inside the hottest loop in the
//      engine (every row fetched by every SELECT filters through it).
//      Keeping the predicate on the row avoids one function-call hop and
//      one extra allocation per tuple.
//
//   4. Soft-delete *and* MVCC.  Older rows predate the MVCC work (Phase 16
//      per the in-line comments) and only have the `deleted` flag.  New
//      rows set `xmin` / `xmax`.  `isVisible` handles both — when
//      `snapshotId == 0` we are in "no active snapshot" mode and fall back
//      to the legacy `deleted` check.  This lets non-transactional
//      callers (REPL, smoke probes, DDL utilities) stay simple while
//      honest transactions get proper read-repeatability.
//
//   5. `clone()` is explicit, not implicit.  Rows are mutable; passing
//      them around by reference is a fine default.  When a path actually
//      needs a detached copy (UPDATE's "old row image" for triggers,
//      savepoint rollback), it calls `clone()` — that way the common
//      case pays nothing.
//
// HOW TO READ THIS FILE
// ---------------------
//   1. Read `./types` first — the `SqlValue` type and the `SQL_*` type
//      codes live there; this file is a consumer.
//   2. Skim the FK action constants to get the vocabulary.
//   3. Read `Column.init()` and `initWithName()` — they establish what a
//      "blank" column looks like, which is what every default-path below
//      starts from.
//   4. Read `Row.isVisible()` carefully — it is the most subtle piece of
//      logic in the file and the one that matters for correctness under
//      concurrent transactions.
//
// =============================================================================

module schema;

// `types.zia` defines `SqlValue` (the tagged-union cell type) and the
// `SQL_*` type codes used in `Column.typeCode`.
bind "./types";

//=============================================================================
// FOREIGN-KEY ACTION CODES
//=============================================================================

// What happens when the referenced row is deleted or its referenced
// column(s) are updated.  Stored as integers on `Column.onDeleteAction`
// and `Column.onUpdateAction`; interpreted by the DML executor.
//
//   NO_ACTION — the default; raise an error if the child row would be
//               orphaned.  In SQL strictly speaking NO ACTION defers the
//               check to end-of-statement, but ViperSQL treats it as
//               RESTRICT (immediate) because we do not implement
//               deferred constraints yet.
//   CASCADE   — propagate: delete child rows when parent is deleted, or
//               rewrite child FK cells when parent key is updated.
//   SET_NULL  — NULL out the child FK columns (only legal when they are
//               not NOT NULL; DDL rejects the mismatch up front).
//   RESTRICT  — same observable behaviour as NO_ACTION for us.
final FK_NO_ACTION = 0;
final FK_CASCADE = 1;
final FK_SET_NULL = 2;
final FK_RESTRICT = 3;

//=============================================================================
// COLUMN
//=============================================================================

/// @brief Everything the engine knows about a single table column.
///
/// A `Column` is pure metadata — it stores no user data itself.  Its
/// lifetime is bound to the `Table` that owns it (see `engine/table.zia`):
/// created by DDL, serialised into a `SCHEMA` page by the storage layer,
/// read back on open, and consulted by every SELECT/INSERT/UPDATE.
///
/// The field set is big because SQL columns *are* big — PRIMARY KEY,
/// UNIQUE, NOT NULL, DEFAULT, CHECK, FOREIGN KEY, GENERATED ALWAYS AS,
/// and named constraints all layer onto the same column object.  Keeping
/// them together (rather than having five parallel tables keyed by
/// column id) means "give me the column" is one lookup that answers every
/// question DDL might ask.
class Column {
    expose String name;
    expose Integer typeCode;          // one of the SQL_* codes from types.zia
    expose Boolean notNull;
    expose Boolean primaryKey;
    expose Boolean autoIncrement;     // PK-only in practice; enforced by DDL
    expose Boolean unique;
    expose Boolean hasDefault;
    expose SqlValue defaultValue;     // meaningful only when hasDefault=true
    expose Boolean isForeignKey;
    expose String refTableName;       // the parent table this FK points at
    expose String refColumnName;      // the parent column
    expose Integer onDeleteAction;    // one of the FK_* constants above
    expose Integer onUpdateAction;
    expose String checkExprSQL;       // the raw CHECK text; re-parsed on use
    // Generated columns (Phase 53) — stored-only, not virtual, so the
    // value lives in the row and the expression is only re-run on
    // INSERT/UPDATE, not on read.
    expose Boolean isGenerated;       // GENERATED ALWAYS AS (<expr>) STORED
    expose String generatedExprSQL;
    // Phase 68: named constraints for better error messages and pg_catalog.
    // Empty string means "no name given"; DDL auto-generates one on demand.
    expose String constraintName;

    /// @brief Zero-state initialiser.
    ///
    /// Produces a TEXT column called "" with no constraints.  Almost
    /// nothing calls this directly — `initWithName` is the usual entry
    /// point because a name and a type are the two fields every column
    /// must have.  `init()` exists mainly so you can instantiate a
    /// Column and then bit-populate it during deserialisation, which is
    /// what `storage/schema_page.zia` does.
    expose func init() {
        name = "";
        typeCode = SQL_TEXT;
        notNull = false;
        primaryKey = false;
        autoIncrement = false;
        unique = false;
        hasDefault = false;
        defaultValue = new SqlValue();
        defaultValue.initNull();
        isForeignKey = false;
        refTableName = "";
        refColumnName = "";
        onDeleteAction = FK_NO_ACTION;
        onUpdateAction = FK_NO_ACTION;
        checkExprSQL = "";
        isGenerated = false;
        generatedExprSQL = "";
        constraintName = "";
    }

    /// @brief Usual constructor: "column named X of type Y, no constraints".
    ///
    /// Called from `engine/ddl.zia` as it walks the CREATE TABLE AST,
    /// adding one column per column-def it encounters.  DDL then flips
    /// individual flags (notNull, primaryKey, …) in response to the
    /// column-constraint list.  That two-step "construct then decorate"
    /// style keeps the Column API small: we do not need one constructor
    /// per possible constraint combination.
    expose func initWithName(n: String, t: Integer) {
        name = n;
        typeCode = t;
        notNull = false;
        primaryKey = false;
        autoIncrement = false;
        unique = false;
        hasDefault = false;
        defaultValue = new SqlValue();
        defaultValue.initNull();
        isForeignKey = false;
        refTableName = "";
        refColumnName = "";
        onDeleteAction = FK_NO_ACTION;
        onUpdateAction = FK_NO_ACTION;
        checkExprSQL = "";
        isGenerated = false;
        generatedExprSQL = "";
        constraintName = "";
    }

    /// @brief Render the type code as its SQL keyword ("INTEGER", "TEXT",
    ///        "JSON", …).
    ///
    /// Used in two places:
    ///   1. `toString()` below — DESCRIBE output, SHOW CREATE TABLE.
    ///   2. `system_views.zia` pg_catalog.pg_attribute implementations.
    ///
    /// NOTE: if a new SQL_* code is added to `types.zia`, add the case
    /// here too — otherwise DESCRIBE will lie by printing "UNKNOWN".
    expose func typeName() -> String {
        if typeCode == SQL_NULL { return "NULL"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_INTEGER { return "INTEGER"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_REAL { return "REAL"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_TEXT { return "TEXT"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_BLOB { return "BLOB"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_BOOLEAN { return "BOOLEAN"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_DATE { return "DATE"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_TIMESTAMP { return "TIMESTAMP"; }
        if typeCode == SQL_JSON { return "JSON"; }
        return "UNKNOWN";
    }

    /// @brief Attach a DEFAULT clause.
    ///
    /// We take the pre-evaluated `SqlValue` (not the raw SQL text) so the
    /// DDL path can evaluate `DEFAULT 1+1` or `DEFAULT CURRENT_TIMESTAMP`
    /// once, at CREATE time, rather than re-parsing it on every INSERT.
    /// For non-deterministic defaults like `CURRENT_TIMESTAMP` the DDL
    /// layer stores a sentinel and re-evaluates on each row insertion —
    /// see `engine/dml.zia::applyDefaults`.
    expose func setDefault(val: SqlValue) {
        hasDefault = true;
        defaultValue = val;
    }

    /// @brief Render the column in SQL-ish form, suitable for SHOW CREATE
    ///        TABLE and DESCRIBE.
    ///
    /// The order of clauses matches the PostgreSQL DESCRIBE layout (name
    /// type [PRIMARY KEY] [AUTOINCREMENT] [NOT NULL] [UNIQUE] [DEFAULT]
    /// [REFERENCES] [GENERATED]) so round-tripping through another SQL
    /// engine remains legal syntax.
    expose func toString() -> String {
        var result = name + " " + typeName();
        if primaryKey {
            result = result + " PRIMARY KEY";
        }
        if autoIncrement {
            result = result + " AUTOINCREMENT";
        }
        if notNull {
            result = result + " NOT NULL";
        }
        if unique {
            result = result + " UNIQUE";
        }
        if hasDefault {
            result = result + " DEFAULT " + defaultValue.toString();
        }
        if isForeignKey {
            result = result + " REFERENCES " + refTableName + "(" + refColumnName + ")";
        }
        if isGenerated {
            result = result + " GENERATED ALWAYS AS (" + generatedExprSQL + ") STORED";
        }
        return result;
    }
}

/// @brief Free-function constructor for `Column` with name+type preset.
///
/// Small sugar — equivalent to `var c = new Column(); c.initWithName(n, t);`
/// in one expression, which makes list-builder code in the DDL pass read
/// more linearly (`columns.add(makeColumn("id", SQL_INTEGER))`).  Not
/// exposed outside the module because callers should prefer constructing
/// through DDL, not wiring columns up by hand.
func makeColumn(name: String, typeCode: Integer) -> Column {
    var col = new Column();
    col.initWithName(name, typeCode);
    return col;
}

//=============================================================================
// ROW
//=============================================================================

/// @brief One row of user data.
///
/// A `Row` is an ordered list of `SqlValue` cells plus two kinds of
/// "is this row visible right now?" metadata:
///
///   * `deleted` — legacy pre-MVCC soft-delete flag.  Still produced by
///                 non-transactional paths (REPL, smoke probes, utility
///                 DDL) and still honoured by the visibility check.
///
///   * `xmin` / `xmax` — MVCC transaction identifiers.  `xmin` is the
///                       txn that *created* this row version; `xmax` is
///                       the txn that *ended* it (via UPDATE or DELETE),
///                       or 0 if it is still live.  See `isVisible`.
///
/// The length of `values` must equal the column count of the owning
/// table — all callers go through DML's validation path before reaching
/// storage, so this invariant is enforced upstream rather than here.
class Row {
    expose List[SqlValue] values;
    expose Boolean deleted;

    // MVCC version tracking (Phase 16).  Both fields default to 0, which
    // means "no MVCC metadata" — honoured by the fallback path in
    // `isVisible()`.
    expose Integer xmin;
    expose Integer xmax;

    /// @brief Empty row: no cells, not deleted, no MVCC stamps.
    ///
    /// Used by clone/split paths that add cells one at a time.
    expose func init() {
        values = [];
        deleted = false;
        xmin = 0;
        xmax = 0;
    }

    /// @brief Fixed-width row with `count` NULL cells.
    ///
    /// Handy for INSERT defaults: DML pre-populates a row of NULLs, then
    /// overwrites individual cells from the VALUES list and the column
    /// defaults.  That avoids the branching "did we set this cell?"
    /// accounting we would otherwise need.
    expose func initWithCount(count: Integer) {
        values = [];
        deleted = false;
        xmin = 0;
        xmax = 0;
        var i = 0;
        while i < count {
            var v = new SqlValue();
            v.initNull();
            values.add(v);
            i = i + 1;
        }
    }

    /// @brief The MVCC visibility predicate.  The single most important
    ///        correctness check in the read path.
    ///
    /// Given a reader's `snapshotId` (the txn id that a SELECT snapshotted
    /// at its BEGIN) and the `currentTxnId` of the reader itself, decide
    /// whether this row should appear in the result set.  Rules:
    ///
    ///   * If `snapshotId == 0` we are in the no-MVCC fallback — the
    ///     caller is not in a transaction (REPL, utility).  Just honour
    ///     the soft-delete flag.
    ///
    ///   * If the legacy `deleted` flag is set, invisible regardless of
    ///     MVCC state.
    ///
    ///   * `xmin` check: the row was created by some transaction.  It is
    ///     visible to us only if that transaction is
    ///       (a) us (currentTxnId), or
    ///       (b) committed before our snapshot (xmin < snapshotId).
    ///     A transaction that committed *after* our snapshot is invisible
    ///     — that is what gives SELECT repeatable-read semantics.
    ///
    ///   * `xmax` check: the row was ended by some transaction.  It is
    ///     invisible if that was us (we deleted it and should not see it
    ///     again), or if the deleter committed before our snapshot.  If
    ///     the deleter committed after — or has not committed at all —
    ///     the row is still visible from our vantage point.
    ///
    /// The interleaving of the two checks is what gives snapshot
    /// isolation: writers see the state of the database frozen at BEGIN
    /// time, concurrent writers do not interfere, and readers never
    /// block.  The cost is that long-running transactions hold onto old
    /// row versions — VACUUM eventually reclaims them once no snapshot
    /// could still need them.
    expose func isVisible(snapshotId: Integer, currentTxnId: Integer) -> Boolean {
        // No snapshot? Fall back to the legacy flag.
        if snapshotId == 0 {
            return deleted == false;
        }

        // Legacy soft-delete wins even in MVCC mode (non-transactional
        // writers to a table that also has MVCC writers still need their
        // deletes to stick).
        if deleted {
            return false;
        }

        // Creator-visibility test.
        if xmin > 0 {
            var xminVisible = false;
            if xmin == currentTxnId {
                xminVisible = true;
            } else if xmin < snapshotId {
                xminVisible = true;
            }
            if xminVisible == false {
                return false;
            }
        }

        // Ender-visibility test.
        if xmax > 0 {
            if xmax == currentTxnId {
                return false;
            }
            if xmax < snapshotId {
                return false;
            }
            // xmax >= snapshotId: the delete happened after our snapshot,
            // so from our vantage point the row is still alive.
        }

        return true;
    }

    /// @brief Number of cells in this row.  Delegates to `values.count()`.
    ///
    /// Exists so that callers that only need the arity do not have to
    /// reach into the `values` list directly — a small encapsulation
    /// convenience for code that reads cleaner as `row.columnCount()`
    /// than `row.values.count()`.
    expose func columnCount() -> Integer {
        return values.count();
    }

    /// @brief Safe cell accessor.
    ///
    /// Returns a fresh NULL `SqlValue` for out-of-range indices rather
    /// than trapping.  This tolerance is important because result-set
    /// code sometimes asks columns of a row (a) that it has since shrunk
    /// or (b) whose projection is out of bounds because the executor and
    /// the planner disagreed on a type — returning NULL keeps rendering
    /// going instead of crashing the whole query.
    expose func getValue(index: Integer) -> SqlValue {
        if index < 0 || index >= values.count() {
            var nullVal = new SqlValue();
            nullVal.initNull();
            return nullVal;
        }
        return values.get(index);
    }

    /// @brief Safe cell setter.
    ///
    /// Silently ignores out-of-range writes.  That ugly tolerance exists
    /// because DML sometimes speculatively sets cells in generated or
    /// trigger-expanded rows whose final arity is only known at the end
    /// of the statement — swallowing the mis-fire is cheaper than
    /// threading a status back through every call site.
    expose func setValue(index: Integer, val: SqlValue) {
        if index >= 0 && index < values.count() {
            values.set(index, val);
        }
    }

    /// @brief Append a cell at the end.
    ///
    /// The deserialization path builds rows this way, reading one cell
    /// from the page at a time and appending.  `initWithCount` is the
    /// pre-allocate-then-setValue alternative; both are used.
    expose func addValue(val: SqlValue) {
        values.add(val);
    }

    /// @brief Deep copy.
    ///
    /// Hand-written rather than a derived clone because `SqlValue` holds
    /// text/blob references that we want to duplicate (or intern) rather
    /// than share — trigger "old row" and "new row" images must not
    /// alias through the cell contents.
    ///
    /// NOTE: only `kind`/`intValue`/`realValue`/`textValue` are copied
    /// here; if new `SqlValue` fields are added to `types.zia`, extend
    /// this loop or cloned rows will silently lose those payloads.
    expose func clone() -> Row {
        var newRow = new Row();
        newRow.init();
        var i = 0;
        while i < values.count() {
            var v = values.get(i);
            var cloned = new SqlValue();
            cloned.kind = v.kind;
            cloned.intValue = v.intValue;
            cloned.realValue = v.realValue;
            cloned.textValue = v.textValue;
            newRow.addValue(cloned);
            i = i + 1;
        }
        newRow.deleted = deleted;
        newRow.xmin = xmin;
        newRow.xmax = xmax;
        return newRow;
    }

    /// @brief Human-readable rendering (e.g. "(1, 'alice', 42)").
    ///
    /// Used mostly for debug logs and in test assertions.  Not on the
    /// wire-protocol path: PG wire encoding goes through typed
    /// per-column writers in `server/pg_wire.zia`.
    expose func toString() -> String {
        var result = "(";
        var i = 0;
        while i < values.count() {
            if i > 0 {
                result = result + ", ";
            }
            result = result + values.get(i).toString();
            i = i + 1;
        }
        result = result + ")";
        return result;
    }
}

/// @brief Free-function row factory: NULL-filled row of the given arity.
///
/// Wraps `Row.initWithCount` for the same reason `makeColumn` wraps
/// `Column.initWithName` — DML code reads more linearly in list-builder
/// style.  Prefer this in new code over `new Row(); row.initWithCount(n)`.
func makeRow(columnCount: Integer) -> Row {
    var row = new Row();
    row.initWithCount(columnCount);
    return row;
}
